  &lt;Comment&gt;
    &lt;Title&gt;Outpatient appointment shambles.&lt;/Title&gt;
    &lt;ScreenName&gt;Anonymous&lt;/ScreenName&gt;
    &lt;CommentText&gt;I received a letter this morning canceling my Neurology Telephone appointment in July 2020 because it is not deemed to be clinically urgent or life-threatening. The main reason it said for doing this is 'to protect you, and limit the risks of transmission of the virus'. Well unless Covid-19 has learned to infect people down the telephone line, I do not feel this letter was appropriate to be sent out to me. I suppose my appointment could have been changed to a hospital face to face outpatient appointment, but if it was, no one told me about it. The letter says they are having to postpone all outpatient appointments. So does this mean the doctors are not even doing Telephone appointments, as this may make me and the doctor at risk of getting Covid-19? Really, I don't think so. I also don't like the tone of the letter. I feel it could scare patients into not ever wanting to attend a hospital outpatient appointment ever again or even entering a hospital at all. I have been attending hospital appointments at other hospitals during the Coronavirus outbreak, and it really isn't that bad. I felt perfectly safe and believe it or not, people do have other medical conditions apart from Covid-19. You wouldn't think so if you are a patient under King's College Hospital. The pandemic is more under control now, and other hospitals are beginning to open up their services to non-coronavirus patients. It would be nice if King's College Hospital could consider doing the same. Non-coronavirus patients also have medical conditions that need to be treated. I have also sent the Consultants I am under emails that haven't been answered, which makes me feel even more ignored.&lt;/CommentText&gt;
